## Attack Simulation: Network Reconnaissance (Nmap)

# Objective

Simulate a reconnaissance phase attack using Nmap to identify exposed services on the target system and evaluate detection capabilities within the Wazuh SIEM.

---

# Target Information

System| Role| IP Address
cloud-lab| Target (Ubuntu Server)| 192.168.56.105
Kali Linux| Attacker| 192.168.56.106

---

# Attack Execution

A TCP connect scan was performed from the attacker machine:

nmap -sT 192.168.56.105

---

# Scan Results

The scan identified the following open ports and services:

- 22/tcp → SSH (OpenSSH)
- 80/tcp → HTTP (Caddy web server)
- 443/tcp → HTTPS

Additional observations:

- Most ports were filtered (no response)
- Target system identified as Linux-based

---

# Detection in Wazuh

❌ No alerts were generated in Wazuh

---

# Analysis

Wazuh operates as a Host-Based Intrusion Detection System (HIDS) and relies on logs generated by the operating system.

The Nmap scan did not trigger authentication attempts or system-level logging events, meaning:

- No entries were written to "/var/log/auth.log"
- No PAM or SSH failures occurred
- No abnormal system activity was detected at the host level

As a result, Wazuh had no data to process or alert on.

---

# Key Insight

«This test demonstrates a limitation of host-based monitoring: reconnaissance activity such as port scanning may go undetected without network-level visibility.»

---

# MITRE ATT&CK Mapping

- T1046 – Network Service Discovery

---

# Security Impact

An attacker can:

- Identify exposed services
- Map the attack surface
- Plan further exploitation (e.g., brute force, web attacks)

---

# Recommendations

To improve detection capabilities:

- Deploy a Network Detection and Response (NDR) solution (e.g., Security Onion)
- Enable logging at the firewall level (pfSense)
- Monitor connection attempts and unusual traffic patterns
- Correlate network and host-based logs

---

# Conclusion

While the Nmap scan successfully identified exposed services, it was not detected by Wazuh due to its host-based nature. This highlights the importance of combining host-based and network-based monitoring for comprehensive security visibility.
